
System Service Commands:
sudo systemctl disable mongod.service

Top 50 Linux cmds

1.`ls`: List files and directories.
2. `cd`: Change directory.
3. `pwd`: Print working directory.
4. `mkdir`: Create a new directory.
5. `rmdir`: Remove a directory (if empty).
6. `rm`: Remove files or directories.
7. `touch`: Create an empty file or update the timestamp.
8. `cp`: Copy files or directories.
9. `mv`: Move or rename files or directories.
10. `cat`: Concatenate and display file content.
11. `more`/`less`: Paginate file content.
12. `head`: Display the beginning of a file.
13. `tail`: Display the end of a file.
14. `grep`: Search for patterns in files or output.
15. `find`: Find files and directories.
16. `chmod`: Change file permissions.
17. `chown`: Change file ownership.
18. `ps`: List running processes.
19. `top`: Display system resource usage and running processes.
20. `kill`: Terminate processes by their PID.
21. `killall`: Terminate processes by name.
22. `ifconfig`: Display network interface information (deprecated, use `ip` instead).
23. `ip`: Display network interface information and configure networking.
24. `ping`: Send ICMP echo requests to a host.
25. `ssh`: Secure Shell client to connect to remote systems.
26. `scp`: Securely copy files between local and remote systems.
27. `wget`: Download files from the web.
28. `tar`: Archive files using tar.
29. `gzip`: Compress files using gzip.
30. `unzip`: Unzip compressed files.
31. `df`: Display disk space usage.
32. `du`: Estimate file and directory space usage.
33. `free`: Display memory usage.
34. `top`: Monitor system performance and processes.
35. `history`: View command history.
36. `date`: Display or set the system date and time.
37. `who`: Display users logged into the system.
38. `whoami`: Display the current user.
39. `passwd`: Change user password.
40. `sudo`: Execute a command with administrative privileges.
41. `adduser`: Create a new user.
42. `userdel`: Delete a user.
43. `groupadd`: Create a new group.
44. `groupdel`: Delete a group.
45. `apt`: Package manager for Ubuntu (e.g., `apt update`, `apt install`, `apt remove`).
46. `dpkg`: Package manager for Debian-based systems (e.g., `dpkg -i`, `dpkg -r`).
47. `shutdown`: Shutdown the system.
48. `reboot`: Reboot the system.
49. `uname`: Display system information (e.g., kernel version, architecture).
50. `lsb_release`: Display Ubuntu release information.

 IMP:  some commands might require administrative privileges, so I have to use `sudo` before them, and always exercise caution when using powerful commands that can modify or delete data.
